-- Anheuser-Busch, Befimmo SCA, BP, Philips, Tesco Plc: Europe Equity Preview
-- Kelly Bit
-- 2010-06-15T04:00:01Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-14/anheuser-busch-befimmo-sca-bp-philips-tesco-plc-europe-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in  European  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are from the last close.  
 The  Stoxx Europe 600 Index  gained 1.2 percent to 252.53.
The  Stoxx 50 Index  rose 0.9 percent to 2,442.73. The  Euro Stoxx
50 Index , a benchmark for nations using the euro, advanced 1.7
percent to 2,683.46.  
 Anheuser-Busch InBev NV  (ABI BB): Patrinvest SCA, a
Luxembourg-based company controlled by Belgium’s Van Damme and
Van der Straten-Ponthoz families, sold 75.2 million euros ($91.9
million) of Anheuser-Busch InBev stock, according to a
regulatory filing. AB InBev gained 1.7 percent to 41 euros.  
 Befimmo SCA  (BEFB BB): Belgium’s second-biggest real estate
investment fund, teaming up with property developers Kairos and
Cavens, agreed to buy Vivaqua’s 15,000 square-meter office in
Brussels for 22.3 million euros, De Tijd reported, without
saying where it got the information. Befimmo dropped 0.9 percent
to 57.31 euros.  
 BP Plc  (BP/ LN): The oil company has hired three banks,
including Blackstone Group LP and Goldman Sachs Group Inc., to
stop a potential hostile takeover, Fox Business Network
reported, citing people familiar with the situation that it
didn’t identify. The stock fell 9.3 percent to 355.45 pence.  
 Royal Philips Electronics NV  (PHIA NA): Europe’s biggest
maker of consumer electronics was raised to “overweight” from
“equal weight” at Morgan Stanley. Philips climbed 3 percent to
25.79 euros.  
 Solvay SA  (SOLB BB): The chemicals and plastics maker that
sold its drug division to Abbott Laboratories said it spent
almost 2.73 million euros buying back an additional 39,065
shares in the three-day period that started June 7. Solvay
increased 2.1 percent to 73.58 euros.  
 Tesco Plc  (TSCO LN): Britain’s biggest retailer is due to
release an interim management statement. The stock fell 0.7
percent to 391.65 pence.  
